    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my civil eng exam and im a bit confused. if concrete is already really strong, why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside it for foundations? like what is the actual relationship between the compressive strength of the concrete and the tensile strength of the steel?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, good question! You see, concrete is indeed a strong material, but it has a weakness - it doesn't do well under tension. It's like a sturdy, unyielding wall, but it has no flexibility. Steel rebar, on the other hand, is like a strong, flexible skeleton that can handle tension and compression. When you mix concrete with steel rebar, you get a structure that can withstand both forces, making it stronger and more resilient. It's like having a sturdy, unyielding wall with a flexible skeleton inside it. So, the compressive strength of the concrete and the tensile strength of the steel work together to create a structure that's both strong and flexible.",
